    pearls: ["Informed consent for prescribing is ONGOING, not a one-time event -- consent must be reassessed when changing doses, adding medications, or when new risks emerge; patients have the right to withdraw consent and discontinue any medication","Present risks using absolute risk and NNT/NNH: telling a patient this statin reduces heart attack risk by 36% (relative risk) is misleading compared to for every 100 people taking this medication for 5 years, 2 will be prevented from having a heart attack (NNT=50)","Black box warnings must be explicitly discussed and documented -- failure to disclose a black box warning is one of the most common bases for prescribing liability claims","Off-label prescribing is legal and often evidence-based, but requires additional informed consent: disclose that the use is not FDA-approved, cite the supporting evidence, and document the discussion and clinical rationale","REMS medications (isotretinoin, clozapine, opioids) have legally mandated consent requirements including specific patient agreements, pregnancy prevention counseling, laboratory monitoring protocols, and documentation","The teach-back method is more reliable than asking do you understand for verifying prescribing consent -- ask patients to explain the medication purpose, dosing, key side effects, and red flags in their own words"],
